    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-15T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-15T07:00:00-05:00" n="449"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d449">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.5151/962: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-15T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 15, 1936—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 15—10:45 a.m.<note n="20" xml:id="d449fn20"
                            >Telegram in two sections.</note>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>870. For Secretary of the Treasury from Cochran. This forenoon I informed
                    Baumgartner of Department’s 348, September 14, 11 p.m., and left with him all of
                    paraphrased text of the British note to us.</p>
                <p>The French had not yet received the text of the British reply to them since
                    Monick is not arriving with it until 4 o’clock this afternoon. In the
                    circumstances Baumgartner will present our communication to the Minister of
                    Finance only after Monick arrives. Baumgartner said they would then call me to
                    the Ministry either tonight or tomorrow.</p>
                <p>Baumgartner sees that we are all in agreement on motives and intentions. His
                    problem is to convince the Minister that the American and British replies offer
                    a sufficient basis for developing the French request for unilateral devaluation
                    in a form that will be accepted by the French public as a realization of
                    international “monetary peace”. The Ministry of Finance is entirely cognizant of
                    the tense situation obtaining here now as a result of labor difficulties and
                    does not want to give the public and particularly the Communists a reason
                    through undisguised devaluation for rioting and perhaps upsetting the
                    Government. [Cochran.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
